<h2>Usage</h2>
<p>Use tabs to organise related content sections or views at the same level of hierarchy on the same page.</p>

<h3>Do</h3>
<ul>
  <li>ensure each tab contains content that is distinct from the others</li>
  <li>use short, scannable and unique tab labels</li>
  <li>keep tab labels on one line and order tabs from most to least important</li>
  <li>include a heading inside every panel that matches the tab label</li>
  <li>use between 2 and 5 tabs for public-facing content</li>
</ul>

<h3>Don&apos;t</h3>
<ul>
  <li>use tabs within tabs</li>
  <li>place accordions inside tab panels as nested navigation</li>
  <li>use tabs as page navigation or site navigation</li>
  <li>use tabs to show progress through a multi-step task; use <a href="/components/progress-indicator/index.html">Progress indicator</a> instead</li>
  <li>display disabled tabs</li>
</ul>

<h2>Mobile behaviour</h2>
<p>Below <code>768px</code>, tabs transform into a same-page link list with all sections visible in document order.</p>
<p>This is an intentional pattern change: on mobile, labels behave as links to content sections rather than tabs that hide and reveal panels.</p>
<ul>
  <li>include a clear heading at the start of each section so stacked content is easy to scan</li>
  <li>keep labels concise and unique so jump links stay meaningful out of context</li>
  <li>use the signpost label before the link list to explain what users can do next</li>
</ul>

<h3>Signpost label guidance</h3>
<p>You can customise the signpost text to suit context (for example, <code>Find information by topic</code> or <code>Explore this guide</code>).</p>
<ul>
  <li>start with an action and a clear object, such as <em>Find</em>, <em>Explore</em>, or <em>Jump to</em></li>
  <li>avoid vague labels that may confuse users about whether they are links or tabs</li>
  <li>keep it short so it supports scanning without competing with section headings</li>
</ul>

<h2>Choose the right pattern</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Tabs</strong>: switch between related sections within the same page region</li>
  <li><strong><a href="/components/in-page-nav/index.html">In-page nav</a> / <a href="/components/side-nav/index.html">Side nav</a></strong>: navigate sections of a page or page group</li>
  <li><strong><a href="/components/main-nav/index.html">Main navigation</a></strong>: navigate across the site or service</li>
  <li><strong><a href="/components/progress-indicator/index.html">Progress indicator</a></strong>: communicate task progress</li>
</ul>

<h3>When to avoid</h3>
<p>Do not:</p>
<ul>
  <li>use where important information can be hidden and missed</li>
  <li>use with very short content, consider using lists or paragraphs</li>
  <li>use for very long content where tab controls become disconnected from the content; consider separate pages</li>
  <li>use for content where users are likely to want to compare information across multiple tabs</li>
</ul>

<h2>Accessibility</h2>
<p>All components are responsive and designed to comply with WCAG 2.2 AA accessibility standards. Full compliance depends on using and configuring the components correctly.</p>

<h3>Keyboard support</h3>
<ul>
  <li>use left and right arrow keys to move between tabs; <code>Home</code> and <code>End</code> jump to first and last tab</li>
  <li>use <code>Tab</code> to move into the active panel content</li>
  <li>use down arrow on the selected tab to move focus to the associated panel</li>
</ul>
<p>For audiences with high assistive-technology usage, run usability testing to confirm whether an alternative hybrid keyboard approach is needed.</p>

<h3>Panel focus</h3>
<p>If a panel contains only static content, keep <code>tabindex=&quot;0&quot;</code> on the <code>tabpanel</code> so keyboard users can move focus into that content region.</p>

<h3>No JavaScript fallback</h3>
<p>Without JavaScript, all tab panels are visible and stacked in document order, and tab labels work as same-page links to each section.</p>

<h3>ARIA requirements</h3>
<ul>
  <li>each tab must map to a real panel via matching <code>href</code> and panel <code>id</code></li>
  <li>where there are more than 3 tabs, include <code>aria-posinset</code> and <code>aria-setsize</code> for each tab</li>
</ul>

<h3>Deep linking</h3>
<p>Tabs support URL hash deep linking. If the page loads with a matching hash, the corresponding panel is opened, and back/forward browser navigation updates the active tab.</p>
